Hook:

Months later, the quiet had taken root. Thorne’s synesthesia was no longer a storm of information, but a subdued palette he could mostly ignore. The labyrinth of the Protocol was a mapped territory in his mind, a dark park he no longer needed to visit. He had chosen a different path: paperwork, cold cases, the reassuringly mundane asymmetry of everyday policing.

He was leaving the station, the autumn air crisp and smelling of leaf smoke, when the desk sergeant called him back. “Post for you, Aris. No stamp, must’ve been hand-delivered.”

It was a plain postcard. A photograph of the Panama Canal, a stark, geometric gash through the continent. On the back, no message, no return address. Just a single, typewritten line:

A MAN, A PLAN, A CANAL – PANAMA.

A perfect, famous palindrome. A joke. A taunt. A greeting.

He stood on the steps of the station, the city’s noise receding into a distant hum. He felt no surge of panic, no compulsive need to deconstruct it. He simply turned the card over in his hands, feeling the weight of the paper, the gloss of the image.

Then, with a faint, weary smile that held no joy, he slowly, deliberately, tore the postcard in half. Then quarters. Then eighths. He let the pieces fall from his fingers, caught by the wind and scattered across the wet pavement.

He turned up his collar and walked away, the pattern finally, definitively, broken behind him. He did not look back.